X-ray of the pelvis shows a fracture of the pubic ramus.  His conditions remains stable over the next hour and a CT scan is undertaken (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supportive treatment and monitoring","Angioembolisation","Ureteric stent","Percutaneous nephrostomy","Right nephrectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFlank pain and haematuria after blunt abdominal trauma are suggestive of renal trauma. Renal trauma is associated with flank pain and tenderness, flank ecchymoses, and haematuria. CT scan with contrast is the diagnostic investigation of choice in haemodynamically stable patients with renal trauma. In patients with contraindications to CT scan with contrast (eg, allergy to contrast, renal failure, haemodynamic instability), ultrasonography may be used to diagnose renal trauma. This patient\u0027s CT scan shows a laceration to the upper pole of the right kidney with some extravasation of contrast. This is a Grade IV injury. The management of the patients with renal trauma depends on haemodynamic status and the grade of renal injury. The majority of patients with renal trauma are managed with \u003Cstrong\u003Esupportive care and monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient is haemodynamically stable and can be managed by monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngioembolisation\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in patients with expanding haematoma or for any clinical deterioration. Surgical management is reserved for patients with severe renal trauma with shattered kidney or those who fail to improve after supportive care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there is any evidence of worsening urinary extravasation, insertion of a \u003Cstrong\u003Estent\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate and is less invasive than a \u003Cstrong\u003Epercutaneous\u003C/strong\u003E approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is only required if he clinically deteriorates and becomes haemodynamically unstable, and embolisation is not successful or available.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Supportive care and surveillance is the preferred management approach for renal trauma."],"references":["Erlich T Renal trauma: the current best practice. Ther Adv Urol 2018, Vol. 10(10) 295\u2013303","Morey AF, Broghammer JA, Hollowell CMP, et al. Urotrauma Guideline 2020: AUA Guideline.  J Urol. 2021; 205:30-35"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92662"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2361"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18469"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18469"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3d1a9bf5-f93e-4cc3-9e8f-0000dbb41967.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3d1a9bf5-f93e-4cc3-9e8f-0000dbb41967.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":419}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92662"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T17:10:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T17:12:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2361"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110389"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","s